'''Bennett Lorber''' is an American medical educator. In 2018 he became professor emeritus at the [[Temple University School of Medicine|Lewis Katz School of Medicine at Temple University]].<ref name="Swarthmore Board of Managers">{{cite web |url=https://www.swarthmore.edu/board-managers/bennett-lorber-64 |title=Bennett Lorber '64 :: Board of Managers :: Swarthmore College |format= |work=Swarthmore College |accessdate=2019-01-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419110817/https://www.swarthmore.edu/board-managers/bennett-lorber-64 |archive-date=2018-04-19 |dead-url=no }}</ref> An authority on the [[listeriosis]] bacterial infection in humans, he has been recognized for the quality of his clinical teaching and has received distinguished teacher awards from the [[Association of American Medical Colleges]] (2018)<ref name="AAMC award">{{cite web |url=https://www.aamc.org/initiatives/awards/2018-aamc-awards-recipients/490584/2018-alpha-omega-glaserd-distinguished-teacher-award.html |title=2018 Alpha Omega Alpha Robert J. Glaser Distinguished Teacher Award; Bennett Lorber |format= |work=Association of American Medical Colleges |accessdate=2019-01-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190126181421/https://www.aamc.org/initiatives/awards/2018-aamc-awards-recipients/490584/2018-alpha-omega-glaserd-distinguished-teacher-award.html |archive-date=2019-01-26 |dead-url=no }}</ref> and the [[American College of Physicians]] (2013).<ref name="AAMC award"/> He also received a lifetime achievement award from the [[Infectious Diseases Society of America]] (2003).<ref name="Antimicrobial Agents"/> He was president of the [[College of Physicians of Philadelphia]] between 2010 and 2012 and of the Anaerobe Society of the Americas between 2008 and 2010.<ref name="Brief Biographical Sketch">{{cite web |url=https://idsa.confex.com/idsa/2013/webprogram/Paper39580.html |title=Brief Biographical Sketch |work=IDWeek 2013, Session 1854. Non-Infectious Causes of Fever |date=2013 |accessdate=2014-04-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622164658/https://idsa.confex.com/idsa/2013/webprogram/Paper39580.html |archive-date=2018-06-22 |dead-url=no }}</ref> 

== Education ==
[[File:BLorberCollegeofPhysiciansofPhiladelphia2014.jpg|thumb|Portrait of Bennett Lorber by Randall Exon, 2014]]
Lorber attended [[Swarthmore College]] where he majored in zoology and art history and graduated with a bachelor of arts degree in 1964.<ref name="Swarthmore Board of Managers"/> He then attended the [[Perelman School of Medicine at the University of Pennsylvania]] and graduated as doctor of medicine in 1968.<ref name="Swarthmore Board of Managers"/> He served an internship (1968–69) and residency in internal medicine (1969–71) and was a Fellow in Infectious Diseases (1971-1973) at [[Temple University School of Medicine#Temple University Hospital|Temple University Hospital]].<ref name="Brief Biographical Sketch"/>

==Career==
In 1973 Lorber joined the faculty of the Temple University School of Medicine.<ref name="AAMC award"/>{{refn|group=note|name=first|In 2015 the Temple University School of Medicine was renamed the Lewis Katz School of Medicine at Temple University. }} He was appointed professor of medicine in 1983 and from 1983 to 2006 served as chief of the school's Section of Infectious Diseases.<ref name="Temple Portrait"/> In 1988 he was named the first recipient of the Thomas Durant Chair in Medicine, a position he held concurrently with that of professor of microbiology and immunology.<ref name="Brief Biographical Sketch"/> 

Lorber has written more than 140 professional articles, a significant number of which have been cited more than 100 times in professional literature.<ref name="Google Scholar 1">{{cite web |url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar?as_sdt=1,21&q=%22bennett+lorber%22&hl=en&as_vis=1  |title=Google Scholar |work= |accessdate=2019-01-27}}</ref> Lorber's article asking "are all diseases infectious?" has been frequently cited and continues to be referenced more than 20 years after its publication. The article appeared in the ''Annals of Internal Medicine'' in November 1996.<ref name="1996 AIM">{{cite journal |author=Bennett Lorber |date=1996-11-15 |title=Are All Diseases Infectious? |url= |journal=Annals of Internal Medicine |volume=125 |issue=10 |pages=844–851 |doi= 10.7326/0003-4819-125-10-199611150-00010|pmc= |pmid=8928993 }}</ref> In 2003, an article of Lorber's was described as a classic in a profile of him appearing in ''Temple Medicine''.<ref name="Temple Medicine Spring-Summer 2003">{{cite journal |author=   |date=2003  |title=Dr. Lorber Honored |url= |journal=Temple Medicine |volume=2003  |issue= FAll-Winter  |page=12 | |pmc= |pmid= }}</ref> Lorber has contributed to every edition of ''Principles and Practice of Infectious Diseases''.<ref name="Change Agent">{{cite journal |vauthors= |date=Summer 2017 |title=Change Agent: Bennett Lorber on Definitions |url=http://www.templehealth.org/thmag/Temple%20Health%20Magazine_Summer2017.pdf |format=PDF |journal=Temple Health Magazine |issue= |page=34 |doi= |pmc= |pmid= |access-date=2017-06-16 }}</ref> He was president of the [[College of Physicians of Philadelphia]] between 2010 and 2012 and of the Anaerobe Society of the Americas between 2008 and 2010.<ref name="Brief Biographical Sketch"/>

=== Clinical work, hospital positions, and research interests ===
Lorber is an authority on [[listeriosis]] and [[anaerobic infection]]s and has studied the impact of societal changes on infectious disease patterns and the relationship between infectious agents and chronic illness.<ref name="listeriosis publications">{{cite web |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed?term=Lorber%20B[Author]&cauthor=true&cauthor_uid=8994747 |title=PubMed citations for Lorber, B. |accessdate=2014-04-29 }}</ref> He was an attending staff physician at Temple University Hospital and Chief of the Section of Infectious Diseases.<ref name="Antimicrobial Agents"/> He has been a consultant in infectious diseases at the [[Fox Chase Cancer Center]] in Philadelphia, the Germantown Hospital and Dispensary, the Philadelphia Geriatric Center, and the [http://www.jeanes.com/content/default.htm Jeanes Hospital], Philadelphia.<ref name="Antimicrobial Agents">{{cite web |url=http://www.antimicrobe.org/authors/benett_lorber.asp |title=Bennett Lorber, MD. DSc (Hon) |work=Antimicrobe, Infectious Disease and Antimicrobial Agents |accessdate=2014-04-28 }}</ref><ref name="Distinguished Teaching Award" />

===Awards and honors===
During his teaching career Lorber received thirteen Golden Apple awards, conferred by the Temple chapter of the [[American Medical Student Association]] for a teacher's outstanding dedication, ability and zeal.<ref name="Temple Portrait">{{cite web |url=https://medicine.temple.edu/news/dr-bennett-lorber-honored-portrait |title=Dr. Bennett Lorber Honored with Portrait |format= |work=Lewis Katz School of Medicine at Temple University |accessdate=2019-01-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190126184204/https://medicine.temple.edu/news/dr-bennett-lorber-honored-portrait |archive-date=2019-01-26 |dead-url=no }}</ref> On two occasions the graduating class at Temple dedicated its yearbook to him (1975, 1988).<ref name="Temple Portrait"/> In 1978 he received Temple's Lindback award for distinguished teaching.<ref name="Lindback Award">{{cite web |url=http://www.temple.edu/provost/faculty/awards/lindback.html |title=Lindback Award, Office of the Provost, Temple University |date=2013 |accessdate=2014-04-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503160954/http://www.temple.edu/provost/faculty/awards/lindback.html  |archive-date=2018-05-03 |dead-url=no }}</ref> He is the only two-time recipient of the Russell and Pearl Moses award for excellence in clinical teaching at Temple (1985, 1990).<ref name="AAMC award"/> He received Temple's Great Teacher Award in 1991.<ref name="Great Teacher Award">{{cite web |url=http://www.temple.edu/provost/faculty/awards/great-teacher.html |title=Great Teacher Award |format= |work=Office of the Provost, Temple University |accessdate=2019-01-28}}</ref> 

In 2004, Lorber was elected to the Academy of Distinguished Educators in Medicine and in 2005 the alumni association of the Temple University School of Medicine presented him with its Honored Professor Award.<ref name="Temple Medicine Fall 2010"/> In 2012 he was named outstanding senior educator by Temple's Department of Medicine.<ref name="Temple Medicine Fall 2010">{{cite journal |author=   |date=2010-11-30  |title=What Ever Happened To? Bennett Lorber, MD |url=https://issuu.com/templemedicine/docs/temple_medicine_fall_2010/42 |journal=Temple Medicine |volume=2010  |issue= Fall  |page=40 }}</ref> In 2013 the American College of Physicians presented Lorber with its distinguished teaching award.<ref name="Distinguished Teaching Award">{{cite web |url=https://www.acponline.org/about-acp/awards-masterships-and-competitions/jane-f-desforges-distinguished-teacher-award |title=Jane F. Desforges Distinguished Teacher Award &#124; Awards, Masterships & Competitions|format= |work=American College of Physicians |accessdate=2019-01-28}}</ref> In 2018 the Association of American Medical Colleges gave him its Distinguished Teacher Award.<ref name="AAMC award"/>

Lorber received the Alexander Fleming Lifetime Achievement Award from the [[Infectious Diseases Society of America]] (2003) granted "in recognition of a career that reflects major contributions to the acquisition and dissemination of knowledge about infectious diseases."<ref name="Alexander Fleming Award Winners">{{cite web |url=https://www.idsociety.org/es/about-idsa/awards/alexander-fleming-award-winners/ |title=Alexander Fleming Award Winners |publisher=Infectious Diseases Society of America 1300 Wilson Boulevard / Suite 300 / Arlington, VA 22209 |date=2013 |accessdate=2014-04-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190126190203/https://www.idsociety.org/es/about-idsa/awards/alexander-fleming-award-winners/ |archive-date=2019-01-26 |dead-url=no}}</ref><ref name="IDSA Alexander Fleming Award">{{cite web |url=http://www.scangrants.com/files/pdfs/grant/2011/4/1/infectious-diseases-society-of-america-alexander-fleming-award.pdf |format=PDF |title=Society of America Alexander Fleming Award |date=2011 |accessdate=2014-04-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129064204/http://www.scangrants.com/files/pdfs/grant/2011/4/1/infectious-diseases-society-of-america-alexander-fleming-award.pdf |archive-date=2019-01-29 |dead-url=yes }}</ref> In 2003 he received the Clinical Practice Award of the Pennsylvania Chapter of the [[American College of Physicians]]. In 2016 he received a Lifetime Achievement Award from the Anaerobe Society of the Americas at their biennial meeting held in Nashville.<ref name="Antimicrobial Agents" /><ref name="Anaerobe">{{cite web |url=http://www.anaerobe.org/2016/2016abBook.pdf |title=13th Biennial Congress of the Anaerobe Society of the Americas |format=PDF |accessdate=2014-04-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831174046/http://www.anaerobe.org/2016/2016abBook.pdf |archive-date=2018-08-31 |dead-url=no}}</ref><ref name="American College of Physicians">{{cite web |url=http://www.playbackacp.com/catalogsearch/result/?q=lorber |title=American College of Physicians, Presenters: Bennett Lorber |accessdate=2014-05-02 }}</ref> 

Lorber was given an honorary doctorate of science by Swarthmore College in 1996.<ref name="Swarthmore Board of Managers"/>  

== Personal life ==
Lorber is a professional artist.<ref name="Anaerobe"/> In an article published in 2015 he wrote that the visual intelligence required of an artist was useful in clinical work, especially in solving diagnostic challenges.<ref name="2015 Better Doctor">{{cite journal |author=Bennett Lorber |date=Autumn 2015 |title=Learn to Look and Be a Better Doctor |url= |journal=Perspectives in Biology and Medicine |volume=58 |issue=4 |page=475 |doi=10.1353/pbm.2015.0040 |pmc= |pmid=27397052 }}</ref> 

